How I came across this was when using Mongoose, if mongo server instance wne don't, it was crashing the process, instead of mongoose trying to reconnect. After narrowing it down it looks to be the Mongo driver that is causing it.

We currently append a {{TransientTransactionError}} label to any {{MongoNetworkError}}, regardless of whether it’s in a transaction or not. This is confusing and makes it seem as though we are implicitly creating a transaction. We should only add this label when we are within a transaction.

[~daniel.aprahamian]'s suggested fix in lib/core/wireprotocol/command.js:

{code}
  const commandResponseHandler = inTransaction
    ? function(err) {
        // Here is what we are changing
        if (err && err instanceof MongoNetworkError && !err.hasErrorLabel('TransientTransactionError') < 0) {
          err.errorLabels.push('TransientTransactionError')
        }
        // Changes end
        if (
          !cmd.commitTransaction &&
          err &&
          err instanceof MongoError &&
          err.hasErrorLabel('TransientTransactionError')
        ) {
          session.transaction.unpinServer();
        }

        return callback.apply(null, arguments);
      }
    : callback;
{code}

We are out of compliance with [this part of the spec|https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/blob/393edc8b07d32de6bb1506a38748b927a7c120fb/source/client-side-encryption/client-side-encryption.rst#auto-encrypt-and-decrypt]:

{quote}
Drivers MUST raise an error when attempting to auto encrypt a command if the maxWireVersion is less than 8. The error message MUST contain "Auto-encryption requires a minimum MongoDB version of 4.2".
{quote}

When performing a bulk write, if there is a BulkWriteError thrown (this is for MongoDB 4.2 and above), the index of the "WriteError" in the error response can be incorrect depending on the order of operations in the bulk write:

If I set up a collection like this in the shell:

{code:javascript}
